{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f5d258eb-66cf-4882-854d-63d19b00d0ab","content":"TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively. Since the project has `OutputType: Exe`, use `dotnet run` with MTP's `--treenode-filter`:\n\n```bash\ndotnet run --project TestProject.csproj -- --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```\n\nThis matches all tests under the `SmsNotificationTests` class (`SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"85cd8594-3d02-418e-8bce-9c575c9c0178","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For TUnit with MTP, the filter syntax uses `--filter-class` or `--treenode-filter`. Let me provide the correct command.\n\nTUnit is built on Microsoft.Testing.Platform. To filter by class, you can use:\n\n```\ndotnet run --project TestProject.csproj -- --filter-class SmsNotificationTests\n```\n\nOr with the fully qualified name:\n\n```\ndotnet run --project TestProject.csproj -- --filter-class Contoso.Notifications.Tests.SmsNotificationTests\n```\n\nSince TUnit projects have `OutputType: Exe` and use MTP natively, `dotnet run` with `--` to pass MTP args is the way to go. Alternatively `dotnet test` may also work depending on configuration.\n\n\nI can also use a treenode filter pattern to match the test class hierarchically, which gives more flexibility in selecting tests across different namespace structures.","outputTokens":397},"id":"229c8493-d021-444a-89a0-8285cf4b036f","timestamp":"2026-04-03T02:18:31.356Z","parentId":"8cb501d0-e40f-40f4-b156-e6b4e88d1afb"}
